            <ArticleTitle>Flagellar determinants of bacterial sensitivity to chi-phage.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>9863-6</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>Bacteriophage chi is known to infect motile strains of enteric bacteria by adsorbing randomly along the length of a flagellar filament and then injecting its DNA into the bacterial cell at the filament base. Here, we provide evidence for a &quot;nut and bolt&quot; model for translocation of phage along the filament: the tail fiber of chi fits the grooves formed by helical rows of flagellin monomers, and active flagellar rotation forces the phage to follow the grooves as a nut follows the threads of a bolt.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
